00:02:57.530 --> 00:03:00.410
and how we can try and
make things better for you

00:03:00.410 --> 00:03:04.040
and also make sure that you have
the right help and tutorials

00:03:04.040 --> 00:03:04.760
and guides.

00:03:08.400 --> 00:03:14.550
With the web as of today, I want
to start with mentioning that,

00:03:14.550 --> 00:03:18.580
because the talk has the
title The Future of the Web.

00:03:18.580 --> 00:03:21.930
But I want to talk about
the web as of today first.

00:03:21.930 --> 00:03:24.510
And if we go back
about six years ago,

00:03:24.510 --> 00:03:26.580
there's something
called Wired magazine.

00:03:26.580 --> 00:03:31.440
And they declared the web
dead about six years ago.

00:03:31.440 --> 00:03:35.140
And this is kind of tiring,
because it becomes always

00:03:35.140 --> 00:03:37.980
this media thing that
something is dying.

00:03:37.980 --> 00:03:40.530
And it's a big crisis.

00:03:40.530 --> 00:03:44.250
Then of course, interestingly
enough, about six years later

00:03:44.250 --> 00:03:45.990
they had a new editor
at the magazine.

00:03:45.990 --> 00:03:49.350
And suddenly the
web was alive again.

00:03:49.350 --> 00:03:52.870
And you hear these
things all the time.

00:03:52.870 --> 00:03:56.820
And if we look only from our
side with Chrome, for instance,

00:03:56.820 --> 00:04:02.700
a year ago Chrome on mobile
alone had 800 million users.

00:04:02.700 --> 00:04:08.250
About six months ago, Chrome on
mobile reached 1 billion users.

00:04:08.250 --> 00:04:10.740
And now Chrome on
mobile and on desktop

00:04:10.740 --> 00:04:13.680
together 2 billion users.

00:04:13.680 --> 00:04:17.010
And that's only one browser out
of many, many different ones.

00:04:17.010 --> 00:04:19.120
So the web is dead?

00:04:19.120 --> 00:04:20.370
Well, not really.

00:04:20.370 --> 00:04:23.070
We don't worry too much
about the headlines.

00:04:23.070 --> 00:04:24.180
And we keep on building.

00:04:24.180 --> 00:04:27.450
And we have more and more people
using the web and building

00:04:27.450 --> 00:04:30.240
things for the web.

00:04:30.240 --> 00:04:33.270
And I think the bad reputation,
especially with the mobile web,

00:04:33.270 --> 00:04:35.190
is that this is what
the experience has

00:04:35.190 --> 00:04:37.410
been like on the mobile
web for a long time.

00:04:37.410 --> 00:04:38.940
You would go into a website.

00:04:38.940 --> 00:04:42.829
You would get a big pop up
telling you to install an app.

00:04:42.829 --> 00:04:44.370
You've never seen
the website before.

00:04:44.370 --> 00:04:46.800
You don't even know if you
want their native app or not.

00:04:46.800 --> 00:04:49.370
But this was the
general experience.

00:04:49.370 --> 00:04:51.520
But it's been
changing over time.

00:04:51.520 --> 00:04:54.510
And if we look now
that on average,

00:04:54.510 --> 00:04:58.870
most smartphone users doesn't
install any new apps any month.

00:04:58.870 --> 00:05:03.890
So if you're one of the top
few apps, WeChat, for instance,

00:05:03.890 --> 00:05:06.640
and a few other ones,
you're really popular.

00:05:06.640 --> 00:05:07.780
You have a lot of users.

00:05:07.780 --> 00:05:09.980
But most other apps
never get those users,

00:05:09.980 --> 00:05:13.770
never gets that engagement.

00:05:13.770 --> 00:05:16.470
And we think, also,
the strength of the web

00:05:16.470 --> 00:05:20.610
is that it's not just
one company or one

00:05:20.610 --> 00:05:22.620
specific platform.

00:05:22.620 --> 00:05:25.870
The web is a myriad
of different browsers.

00:05:25.870 --> 00:05:27.840
There's so many different
browsers on desktop

00:05:27.840 --> 00:05:30.870
and on mobile out there.

00:05:30.870 --> 00:05:33.210
And what I will talk
about a bit today

00:05:33.210 --> 00:05:38.430
is both learnings that we've had
about the web and also things

00:05:38.430 --> 00:05:40.520
that we have
implemented in Chrome

00:05:40.520 --> 00:05:42.540
and that we're starting
to implement Chrome.

00:05:42.540 --> 00:05:45.360
Not just to talk about
Chrome, but also things

00:05:45.360 --> 00:05:48.290
that we would love to see
standardized and things that we

00:05:48.290 --> 00:05:52.220
would love to see in
any browser out there.

00:05:52.220 --> 00:05:54.980
And also when I talk
about the web as today,

00:05:54.980 --> 00:05:56.490
it's generally
progressive web apps.

00:05:56.490 --> 00:06:00.290
Progressive web apps is the
entire thing, the entire way

00:06:00.290 --> 00:06:04.100
of making sure that we
build really good websites

00:06:04.100 --> 00:06:08.030
and then also adding on even
more greater capabilities

00:06:08.030 --> 00:06:11.190
that we've seen from
the native world.

00:06:11.190 --> 00:06:14.280
And I'm going to go through
six of them really quickly.

00:06:14.280 --> 00:06:17.180
And the first one, when we
talk about progress web apps,

00:06:17.180 --> 00:06:19.130
we want to see instant loading.

00:06:19.130 --> 00:06:21.020
Using something
like Service Workers

00:06:21.020 --> 00:06:24.290
to make sure that you
have offline access,

00:06:24.290 --> 00:06:26.630
but even more importantly
in places where

00:06:26.630 --> 00:06:30.920
you have poor connectivity
or intermittent connectivity,

00:06:30.920 --> 00:06:35.210
to make sure that you can have
a faster loading experience.

00:06:35.210 --> 00:06:37.910
The next one is
adding to home screen.

00:06:37.910 --> 00:06:41.360
As we see with users, having
an icon on the home screen

00:06:41.360 --> 00:06:43.280
leads to great re-engagement.

00:06:43.280 --> 00:06:47.310
And people just keep
on using the app.

00:06:47.310 --> 00:06:49.300
The third one is
push notification.

00:06:49.300 --> 00:06:52.600
And that was covered in
Sam's presentation before.

00:06:52.600 --> 00:06:55.240
But just seeing
re-engagement from users,

00:06:55.240 --> 00:06:57.697
and notifications
can be terrible.

00:06:57.697 --> 00:06:59.030
And they can be really annoying.

00:06:59.030 --> 00:07:01.580
But if you do them well, they
can be really, really good

00:07:01.580 --> 00:07:04.770
and useful for your app as well.

00:07:04.770 --> 00:07:10.172
The fourth one is making sure
that your web app is fast.

00:07:10.172 --> 00:07:12.380
And it's not only about
loading fast, but making sure

00:07:12.380 --> 00:07:16.280
that the animations you have in
the web app is fast and smooth.

00:07:16.280 --> 00:07:18.580
And when you scroll
or if you move around,

00:07:18.580 --> 00:07:22.600
it's a nice, good experience.

00:07:22.600 --> 00:07:25.210
Also that it's secure.

00:07:25.210 --> 00:07:29.260
Basically for more or less
any of the new APIs coming out

00:07:29.260 --> 00:07:32.170
right now, you have HTTPS.

00:07:32.170 --> 00:07:33.550
That's one of the requirements.

00:07:33.550 --> 00:07:35.830
And we're also
implementing HTTPS

00:07:35.830 --> 00:07:38.410
for older APIs
like geo location,

00:07:38.410 --> 00:07:41.950
because we see this as a
really necessary thing.

00:07:41.950 --> 00:07:44.470
And we're also experimenting
with some things

00:07:44.470 --> 00:07:47.800
in Chrome, because
before, if would access

00:07:47.800 --> 00:07:51.925
a website over an
unsecure connection, HTTP,

00:07:51.925 --> 00:07:53.050
you would just see the URL.

00:07:53.050 --> 00:07:54.730
And then we started
experimenting

00:07:54.730 --> 00:07:58.996
with writing in the URL
bar that it's not secure.

00:07:58.996 --> 00:08:00.370
And then over
time, it might look

00:08:00.370 --> 00:08:02.590
like something at the
bottom that we will actually

00:08:02.590 --> 00:08:06.040
really start warning users
that any website that you have

00:08:06.040 --> 00:08:08.380
an interaction with
has to be secure,

00:08:08.380 --> 00:08:14.110
both for that website's sake but
also for your sake as a user.

00:08:14.110 --> 00:08:17.050
The final one, of course,
is making it responsive.

00:08:17.050 --> 00:08:19.942
If you build a mobile
web app, mobile website,

00:08:19.942 --> 00:08:21.400
you want to make
sure that it works

00:08:21.400 --> 00:08:25.840
on any kind of resolutions
from different mobile devices,

00:08:25.840 --> 00:08:28.760
to tablets, to desktops.

00:08:28.760 --> 00:08:32.090
So in a summary,
progressive web apps

00:08:32.090 --> 00:08:37.370
today need to be reliable,
fast, engaging, and secure.

00:08:37.370 --> 00:08:39.919
And the core of all
this is making sure

00:08:39.919 --> 00:08:44.144
that your users have
a good experience.

00:08:44.144 --> 00:08:47.310
Experiences that are good
will have users coming back.

00:08:47.310 --> 00:08:49.590
And happy users will
lead to happy developers

00:08:49.590 --> 00:08:52.420
and happy companies.

00:08:52.420 --> 00:08:54.270
And if you look back
only a few years,

00:08:54.270 --> 00:08:57.180
we've come a really long
way on the web and things

00:08:57.180 --> 00:09:00.030
that are being supported now.

00:09:00.030 --> 00:09:02.310
We had to implement a
number of different APIs

00:09:02.310 --> 00:09:04.440
and support a number
of different things.

00:09:04.440 --> 00:09:06.322
And more or less, one
of the only things

00:09:06.322 --> 00:09:08.280
that you can't do on the
web right now that you

00:09:08.280 --> 00:09:13.300
can do native is having contact
access on your mobile phones.

00:09:13.300 --> 00:09:17.640
So I really want you to remember
that the web is already all

00:09:17.640 --> 00:09:19.900
mighty powerful.

00:09:19.900 --> 00:09:23.850
I really hope that that is what
the Chinese characters means.

00:09:23.850 --> 00:09:26.350
I should have translated this.

00:09:26.350 --> 00:09:29.434
But at the same time,
it's just the beginning.

00:09:34.650 --> 00:09:37.140
All those things that
we've done so far,

00:09:37.140 --> 00:09:39.800
you see notifications at the
home screen and all of that,

00:09:39.800 --> 00:09:42.060
it's just making sure that
we can match the experience

00:09:42.060 --> 00:09:46.530
that native has both
offered users, but also

00:09:46.530 --> 00:09:48.720
the expectations that are
set with users that this

00:09:48.720 --> 00:09:49.920
is what users want.

00:09:49.920 --> 00:09:52.990
And we should
bring that to them.

00:09:52.990 --> 00:09:57.832
So finally, 32 slides later,
what about the future?

00:09:57.832 --> 00:09:59.540
What are the new things
that we're doing?

00:09:59.540 --> 00:10:02.160
And when I refer
to the future, I

00:10:02.160 --> 00:10:06.510
can talk about very
many crazy things.

00:10:06.510 --> 00:10:09.030
But I'm not going to talk
about building robots

00:10:09.030 --> 00:10:12.630
from old mobile phones and then
controlling them or something.

00:10:12.630 --> 00:10:15.150
When I talk about the future,
and what I think is important

00:10:15.150 --> 00:10:19.680
is something that you
can use now or very soon,

00:10:19.680 --> 00:10:21.210
something that's
actually coming.

00:10:21.210 --> 00:10:23.269
I don't want to say that
maybe in five years,

00:10:23.269 --> 00:10:24.060
you will have this.

00:10:24.060 --> 00:10:27.420
I want it to be
relevant for you now.

00:10:27.420 --> 00:10:30.360
So the things I'll be
talking about today

00:10:30.360 --> 00:10:34.650
is knowing who the user
is, credentials management,

00:10:34.650 --> 00:10:38.070
paying for things on the web,
connecting with hardware,

00:10:38.070 --> 00:10:41.950
physical web, and web VR.

00:10:41.950 --> 00:10:45.020
And first, with knowing
who the user is.

00:10:45.020 --> 00:10:49.290
It's all about the challenges
on the mobile web with sign in.

00:10:49.290 --> 00:10:51.300
And usually if you come
to a mobile website,

00:10:51.300 --> 00:10:52.591
then you're supposed to log in.

00:10:52.591 --> 00:10:54.270
And you see all of this.

00:10:54.270 --> 00:10:56.220
And it's seldom a
good experience,

00:10:56.220 --> 00:11:00.100
because when you see this,
you start thinking about this.

00:11:00.100 --> 00:11:04.110
Did I use Facebook or Google or
any other account to sign up?

00:11:04.110 --> 00:11:06.900
Usually you know
your email address.

00:11:06.900 --> 00:11:08.730
You will never remember
the password you

00:11:08.730 --> 00:11:10.830
use for this specific website.

00:11:10.830 --> 00:11:12.540
So you sit there and
you're wondering,

00:11:12.540 --> 00:11:13.830
and you go through the page.

00:11:13.830 --> 00:11:17.690
And then you find the magical
link, the forgot password link.

00:11:17.690 --> 00:11:22.410
Has anyone not used
forgot password?

00:11:22.410 --> 00:11:24.320
Good, we're among friends.

00:11:24.320 --> 00:11:27.000
It's OK.

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:31.200
And also a really hard
part is on mobile keywords,

00:11:31.200 --> 00:11:33.300
it's really hard to type.

00:11:33.300 --> 00:11:35.050
You have a small keyboard.

00:11:35.050 --> 00:11:37.410
And getting the right
characters in the right order,

00:11:37.410 --> 00:11:42.310
and you're supposed to be
fast, isn't always easy,

00:11:42.310 --> 00:11:43.920
which leads to a problem.

00:11:43.920 --> 00:11:47.130
Do you know what this is?

00:11:47.130 --> 00:11:48.640
Yes, password.

00:11:48.640 --> 00:11:55.100
This is the most popular
password in 2015.

00:11:55.100 --> 00:11:59.150
Interestingly
enough, it actually

00:11:59.150 --> 00:12:01.520
bumped down to second
most popular password,

00:12:01.520 --> 00:12:04.140
which had been the most
popular for many years,

00:12:04.140 --> 00:12:06.430
which was actually
the word password.

00:12:09.360 --> 00:12:12.480
So it's fun.

00:12:12.480 --> 00:12:17.050
But it also poses an
enormous security risk.

00:12:17.050 --> 00:12:20.040
And especially because everyone
is reusing their password

00:12:20.040 --> 00:12:22.980
across websites and all of
that, and if one password or one

00:12:22.980 --> 00:12:27.670
service leaks their passwords,
there's nothing you can do.

00:12:27.670 --> 00:12:30.030
So one thing that we started
doing from the Chrome side

00:12:30.030 --> 00:12:32.071
and trying to see if we
can help from the browser

00:12:32.071 --> 00:12:34.770
is introducing something
called Smart Lock.

00:12:34.770 --> 00:12:38.390
And now with Smart Lock, we
have about 8 billion sign ins

00:12:38.390 --> 00:12:42.210
that we assist through
Chrome every month.

00:12:42.210 --> 00:12:46.050
And basically either
this just works for you.

00:12:46.050 --> 00:12:47.640
Or as a developer,
you might need

00:12:47.640 --> 00:12:51.720
to do really, really small
things in your website,

00:12:51.720 --> 00:12:53.970
because generally when a
browser comes to your website

00:12:53.970 --> 00:12:56.910
and reads out the forms, it
sees all the different fields.

00:12:56.910 --> 00:12:58.590
And sometimes they're
really obvious.

00:12:58.590 --> 00:13:01.500
And the browser will know
what to do and what to store.

00:13:01.500 --> 00:13:03.980
But sometimes it
isn't entirely clear.

00:13:03.980 --> 00:13:07.350
So something that you can use
is the autocomplete attribute.

00:13:07.350 --> 00:13:09.980
So you can help the
browser understand

00:13:09.980 --> 00:13:12.320
what each field actually means.

00:13:12.320 --> 00:13:13.830
So OK, this is the name.

00:13:13.830 --> 00:13:15.120
This is the telephone number.

00:13:15.120 --> 00:13:18.100
This is the username, et cetera.

00:13:18.100 --> 00:13:21.280
And if you have a sign
in form, for instance,

00:13:21.280 --> 00:13:23.320
you can use autocomplete
and just specify

00:13:23.320 --> 00:13:24.745
that this is the username.

00:13:24.745 --> 00:13:26.120
And this is the
current password.

00:13:28.780 --> 00:13:32.560
And for sign up forms, when
you're creating a new account

00:13:32.560 --> 00:13:33.890
you can have the same things.

00:13:33.890 --> 00:13:36.230
But one interesting
part here is you

00:13:36.230 --> 00:13:39.340
can see that we have
autocomplete new password

00:13:39.340 --> 00:13:42.610
instead of current
password or just password.

00:13:42.610 --> 00:13:45.260
And there are two
important reasons for that.

00:13:45.260 --> 00:13:48.130
One is if you have
Autofill in your browser,

00:13:48.130 --> 00:13:50.710
just making sure that when you
create a new account that it

00:13:50.710 --> 00:13:53.160
doesn't reduce what
you already have stored

00:13:53.160 --> 00:13:55.060
or something like that.

00:13:55.060 --> 00:13:57.160
But a second one, which
is really interesting,

00:13:57.160 --> 00:14:00.190
is that if we, from
the browser side,

00:14:00.190 --> 00:14:02.740
knows that the user
needs a new password,

00:14:02.740 --> 00:14:06.440
we can auto generate
it from the browser.

00:14:06.440 --> 00:14:11.770
So for users, instead of them
having passwords like this,

00:14:11.770 --> 00:14:14.120
we can give them
this as a password,

00:14:14.120 --> 00:14:15.970
I mean not specifically
this, because that

00:14:15.970 --> 00:14:18.610
wouldn't be very secure,
because you've seen this now.

00:14:18.610 --> 00:14:21.970
But more secure
passwords for them that

00:14:21.970 --> 00:14:25.360
might not be easy to remember,
but it will make them safer

00:14:25.360 --> 00:14:26.440
on the web.

00:14:26.440 --> 00:14:28.280
And we're
experimenting with auto

00:14:28.280 --> 00:14:32.350
entering passwords in Chrome and
then deploying it more and more

00:14:32.350 --> 00:14:33.160
widely.

00:14:33.160 --> 00:14:35.830
So please make sure to
mark up your forms today

00:14:35.830 --> 00:14:37.810
with the autocomplete
attribute, because it's

00:14:37.810 --> 00:14:40.240
a really small task to do.

00:14:40.240 --> 00:14:42.610
But it means a lot for the
browser and for the users

00:14:42.610 --> 00:14:44.720
as well.

00:14:44.720 --> 00:14:46.970
Then we have the
credentials management API,

00:14:46.970 --> 00:14:50.446
which is the next generation
for sign-in on the web.

00:14:50.446 --> 00:14:52.070
And we shipped this
recently in Chrome.

00:14:52.070 --> 00:14:54.650
It's not in all browsers yet.

00:14:54.650 --> 00:14:56.300
And it allows you,
as a developer,

00:14:56.300 --> 00:14:58.960
to integrate with the
browsers Credential Manager.

00:15:05.920 --> 00:15:08.830
And for instance,
with Ali Express,

00:15:08.830 --> 00:15:12.950
they have a really good example
of a good user sign in flow.

00:15:12.950 --> 00:15:15.100
Being a shopping app,
it's really important

00:15:15.100 --> 00:15:15.790
to be signed in.

00:15:15.790 --> 00:15:17.290
But at the same
time, you don't want

00:15:17.290 --> 00:15:20.470
to block to user with
having a big login pop-up

00:15:20.470 --> 00:15:23.110
or something like that or
blocking the experience.

00:15:23.110 --> 00:15:25.300
So as you can see
at the bottom here,

00:15:25.300 --> 00:15:28.100
we're offering them
automatic sign-in

00:15:28.100 --> 00:15:31.300
on the web, which
is really nice.

00:15:31.300 --> 00:15:33.790
And code wise, it's
quite easy to do.

00:15:33.790 --> 00:15:36.940
You use something called
navigator.credentials.

00:15:36.940 --> 00:15:39.910
And then you call the get
method to get the password

00:15:39.910 --> 00:15:41.680
and sign them in.

00:15:41.680 --> 00:15:43.300
The interesting
and important part

00:15:43.300 --> 00:15:47.130
here is where you see
what it says unmediated.

00:15:47.130 --> 00:15:49.510
And what unmediated
means is that it

00:15:49.510 --> 00:15:53.040
will be no prompt or nothing
blocking the experience.

00:15:53.040 --> 00:15:54.760
It will just be done
in the background

00:15:54.760 --> 00:15:58.340
automatically for the user.

00:15:58.340 --> 00:16:01.810
For automatic sign-in
and from the Chrome site

00:16:01.810 --> 00:16:06.770
to get it to work, automatic
sign-in needs to be enabled.

00:16:06.770 --> 00:16:08.300
And you can only
have one credential

00:16:08.300 --> 00:16:11.420
saved for that website.

00:16:11.420 --> 00:16:14.810
Also as mentioned before, and
as many, many other things,

00:16:14.810 --> 00:16:18.500
navigator.credentials needs
to be served over HTTPS.

00:16:18.500 --> 00:16:20.900
So it has to be
a secure context.

00:16:20.900 --> 00:16:24.230
Naturally passwords aren't
directly exposed to JavaScript.

00:16:24.230 --> 00:16:26.870
And also the fetch method
would only submit credentials

00:16:26.870 --> 00:16:30.070
to the same site endpoint.

00:16:30.070 --> 00:16:32.840
So once you've gotten the
credentials from the user.

00:16:32.840 --> 00:16:36.300
You can use fetch and just
send that into the server.

00:16:36.300 --> 00:16:41.420
Pass in the credentials, and
verify them, and log them in.

00:16:41.420 --> 00:16:43.210
If that isn't an
option for you, you

00:16:43.210 --> 00:16:47.620
can use one-tap sign-in, which
is more of having the prompter.

00:16:47.620 --> 00:16:48.820
So you go to the website.

00:16:48.820 --> 00:16:49.810
The prompt comes up.

00:16:49.810 --> 00:16:51.070
You choose your account.

00:16:51.070 --> 00:16:53.070
And you sign-in.

00:16:53.070 --> 00:16:57.150
And code wise, it looks almost
exactly as what you saw before.

00:16:57.150 --> 00:16:58.960
The only thing
that's been removed

00:16:58.960 --> 00:17:02.320
is the word where
we had unmediated.

00:17:02.320 --> 00:17:05.569
Otherwise it's
just the same code.

00:17:05.569 --> 00:17:08.800
And getting the credentials
and sign-in them automatically

00:17:08.800 --> 00:17:10.660
is great.

00:17:10.660 --> 00:17:13.410
But you also want to give
the developers the ability

00:17:13.410 --> 00:17:17.032
to choose when the save the
password prompt is triggered.

00:17:17.032 --> 00:17:18.990
When should this actually
come up for the user?

00:17:18.990 --> 00:17:21.130
When is a good time?

00:17:21.130 --> 00:17:23.805
And the way you can do that
is that you, for instance, can

00:17:23.805 --> 00:17:25.890
get a reference to the form.

00:17:25.890 --> 00:17:28.200
And then you create
a new password

00:17:28.200 --> 00:17:31.050
credential object
and pass in that form

00:17:31.050 --> 00:17:32.890
and then store that value.

00:17:32.890 --> 00:17:36.120
So again, just a nicer user
experience when it makes sense

00:17:36.120 --> 00:17:38.370
to actually store that,
instead of blocking them

00:17:38.370 --> 00:17:41.280
in the middle of
doing something.

00:17:41.280 --> 00:17:44.620
We also support federated
logins through the Credential

00:17:44.620 --> 00:17:47.020
Management API, which
could be Facebook

00:17:47.020 --> 00:17:50.200
and Google and other accounts.

00:17:50.200 --> 00:17:52.270
And doing that,
it's just creating

00:17:52.270 --> 00:17:54.790
a new federated
credential object.

00:17:54.790 --> 00:17:56.320
And you pass in the username.

00:17:56.320 --> 00:18:01.250
And you also pass in the URL
of the provider for the login.

00:18:01.250 --> 00:18:04.890
And the browser will deal
with the rest of the process.

00:18:04.890 --> 00:18:08.990
It's also important to
let the user be logged out

00:18:08.990 --> 00:18:10.150
when they're done.

00:18:10.150 --> 00:18:11.816
And especially if
you're using something

00:18:11.816 --> 00:18:13.610
like Autofill or
automatic sign-in,

00:18:13.610 --> 00:18:15.410
you don't want to
automatically be sign-in

00:18:15.410 --> 00:18:19.070
if someone else loads
it or has access to it.

00:18:19.070 --> 00:18:21.920
So you can just call
requireUserMediation

00:18:21.920 --> 00:18:24.290
to log them out.

00:18:24.290 --> 00:18:26.300
And we've seen a number
of companies starting

00:18:26.300 --> 00:18:27.800
working with this already.

00:18:27.800 --> 00:18:31.130
And some of them have
it in production.

00:18:31.130 --> 00:18:34.730
So we shipped this
back in Chrome 51.

00:18:34.730 --> 00:18:36.590
So please try out
these websites.

00:18:36.590 --> 00:18:40.350
And try out that experience.

00:18:40.350 --> 00:18:43.050
Next I want to talk about
paying for things on the web.

00:18:43.050 --> 00:18:47.550
And I think this is probably
the most important topic.

00:18:47.550 --> 00:18:50.320
If we see the success
of native apps,

00:18:50.320 --> 00:18:52.050
it's been mainly
based on how easy it

00:18:52.050 --> 00:18:55.170
to pay for things, to get
apps or services or something

00:18:55.170 --> 00:18:58.350
like that, and then just keep
on using what you're using.

00:18:58.350 --> 00:19:02.220
And we really need to get
this right on the web.

00:19:02.220 --> 00:19:04.055
And with the rise
of mobile computing,

00:19:04.055 --> 00:19:06.180
the majority of
commercial traffic

00:19:06.180 --> 00:19:08.700
is coming from mobile devices.

00:19:08.700 --> 00:19:11.160
And even though it's been
good in native, what's

00:19:11.160 --> 00:19:16.710
really surprising is that
still, 66% of purchases

00:19:16.710 --> 00:19:20.310
on mobile devices are on
the web, not native apps,

00:19:20.310 --> 00:19:22.080
through the mobile web.

00:19:22.080 --> 00:19:27.360
So the web, again,
isn't really dead yet.

00:19:27.360 --> 00:19:30.030
And we looked at some
countries in Europe

00:19:30.030 --> 00:19:32.460
and seeing how many of them
were using the mobile web.

00:19:38.030 --> 00:19:39.790
And as you can see,
it's sort of a trend.

00:19:39.790 --> 00:19:44.520
It's around 66% per country.

00:19:44.520 --> 00:19:48.600
And also a bit small,
but we can also

00:19:48.600 --> 00:19:51.630
see, which I really find
interesting digging into,

00:19:51.630 --> 00:19:55.410
is seeing four different
actions what users prefer

00:19:55.410 --> 00:19:58.590
to use to do that,
if they want to use

00:19:58.590 --> 00:20:03.230
a website or an application
or something like that.

00:20:03.230 --> 00:20:04.450
So that's great.

00:20:04.450 --> 00:20:08.680
People are already,
despite some annoyances,

00:20:08.680 --> 00:20:11.110
shopping on the mobile web.

00:20:11.110 --> 00:20:16.900
But still we see 66% fewer
conversions on the mobile web

00:20:16.900 --> 00:20:19.210
versus desktop websites.

00:20:19.210 --> 00:20:22.750
So it's still a lot of
money, a lot of shopping.

00:20:22.750 --> 00:20:24.110
But it could be a lot more.

00:20:24.110 --> 00:20:26.450
We could to help
users a lot more.

00:20:26.450 --> 00:20:30.130
And the reason why it's so much
lower on mobile, of course,

00:20:30.130 --> 00:20:34.120
is it's still hard on mobile.

00:20:34.120 --> 00:20:36.970
And usually you see
a number of people

00:20:36.970 --> 00:20:40.440
just giving up in
the check out flow

00:20:40.440 --> 00:20:43.610
when they're trying to
finalize their purchase.

00:20:43.610 --> 00:20:47.110
So looking at check out
forums today [INAUDIBLE],

00:20:47.110 --> 00:20:49.220
they are manual.

00:20:49.220 --> 00:20:50.110
They are tedious.

00:20:50.110 --> 00:20:52.680
They take a lot of
time to fill out,

00:20:52.680 --> 00:20:56.170
and also requires a
certain amount of taps

00:20:56.170 --> 00:20:57.880
to actually get
through all of that.

00:20:57.880 --> 00:20:59.830
And on all mobile
keyboard's, if you're

00:20:59.830 --> 00:21:03.260
supposed to, for instance, type
in your credit card number,

00:21:03.260 --> 00:21:06.130
16 numbers, and you don't
even get the number keyboard

00:21:06.130 --> 00:21:08.680
on your phone, it's hard.

00:21:08.680 --> 00:21:09.430
And it's annoying.

00:21:09.430 --> 00:21:12.330
And people give up.

00:21:12.330 --> 00:21:16.680
So again trying to balance
it from the browser side,

00:21:16.680 --> 00:21:19.680
we're working with
Autofill, just making sure

00:21:19.680 --> 00:21:22.045
that you can start
something in one field

00:21:22.045 --> 00:21:23.670
and then just fill
out the entire form.

00:21:23.670 --> 00:21:25.440
Because usually when
you fill out forms,

00:21:25.440 --> 00:21:27.750
you more or less fill it
out with the same data

00:21:27.750 --> 00:21:30.450
as you're done before.

00:21:30.450 --> 00:21:33.540
And the way Autofill
works is just

00:21:33.540 --> 00:21:35.700
storing the user's
address and credit

00:21:35.700 --> 00:21:38.910
card and different
things into the browser

00:21:38.910 --> 00:21:41.150
and then having
automatic form detection.

00:21:41.150 --> 00:21:46.250
And we see about 95%
accuracy with our Autofill.

00:21:46.250 --> 00:21:49.020
And then also if
you want to, Chrome

00:21:49.020 --> 00:21:51.180
can synchronize that
securely between

00:21:51.180 --> 00:21:52.770
all your different devices.

00:21:52.770 --> 00:21:54.770
So for instance, if you
use Chrome on your phone

00:21:54.770 --> 00:21:57.660
and your desktop all
your Autofill information

00:21:57.660 --> 00:22:00.240
can be synchronized
between those two.

00:22:00.240 --> 00:22:03.990
And when it comes to conversion
rate, with Autofill alone,

00:22:03.990 --> 00:22:07.894
we now see 25%
increase in conversion.

00:22:07.894 --> 00:22:08.560
So that's great.

00:22:08.560 --> 00:22:12.930
And then we can't really do
everything to make it happen.

00:22:12.930 --> 00:22:15.120
But it's one of the
steps of getting

00:22:15.120 --> 00:22:18.640
closer to where it should be.

00:22:18.640 --> 00:22:21.120
So Autofill's been good.

00:22:21.120 --> 00:22:22.660
It's being more automatic.

00:22:22.660 --> 00:22:24.980
And it's making it simple.

00:22:24.980 --> 00:22:27.430
But it's still slow with
forms on the the web.

00:22:27.430 --> 00:22:30.460
And it still takes a
certain amount of taps.

00:22:30.460 --> 00:22:33.610
So imagine a world
without forms.

00:22:33.610 --> 00:22:37.360
And it would be
an amazing world.

00:22:37.360 --> 00:22:40.210
And that's actually
what we're trying to do.

00:22:40.210 --> 00:22:43.450
And with something
called PaymentRequest.

00:22:43.450 --> 00:22:48.640
And PaymentRequest is
W3C API to just eliminate

00:22:48.640 --> 00:22:51.940
all kinds of checkout paints.

00:22:51.940 --> 00:22:54.030
And it's a simple
JavaScript API.

00:22:54.030 --> 00:22:56.380
And the browser will take
care of the complicated parts

00:22:56.380 --> 00:22:57.370
of the payment.

00:22:57.370 --> 00:23:00.910
And you can actually
get a one tap checkout.

00:23:00.910 --> 00:23:07.050
And this is also an openly
developed standard API.

00:23:07.050 --> 00:23:11.870
Currently it's under development
in W3C Payments Working Group.

00:23:11.870 --> 00:23:16.470
And their idea is to create
universal cross-browser

00:23:16.470 --> 00:23:18.090
standard for any website.

00:23:18.090 --> 00:23:21.390
So this is not a
Chrome only API.

00:23:21.390 --> 00:23:24.110
We really want to see it
across all major browsers.

00:23:24.110 --> 00:23:28.050
And we see interest from all
the big browsers actually doing

00:23:28.050 --> 00:23:28.660
this as well.

00:23:28.660 --> 00:23:31.050
For instance, Microsoft have
been doing lots of good work

00:23:31.050 --> 00:23:33.080
around this.

00:23:33.080 --> 00:23:36.670
And the implementation that
we started doing in Chrome

00:23:36.670 --> 00:23:39.820
has been on mobile first.

00:23:39.820 --> 00:23:41.920
But then of course, over
time we want to make sure

00:23:41.920 --> 00:23:43.720
that it's cross platform.

00:23:43.720 --> 00:23:46.210
So it works on desktop
and any other device

00:23:46.210 --> 00:23:48.610
as well, and also
that we can support

00:23:48.610 --> 00:23:51.430
an open ecosystem of
different payment methods

00:23:51.430 --> 00:23:54.740
as well, which of
course is important.

00:23:54.740 --> 00:23:57.770
So going back to
the pain of forms,

00:23:57.770 --> 00:24:00.530
now with Autofill
and PaymentRequest,

00:24:00.530 --> 00:24:03.470
we can get rid of
pretty much everything.

00:24:03.470 --> 00:24:07.250
So we can now make it fast and
go from many different taps

00:24:07.250 --> 00:24:09.440
to just one tap
checkouts, which is

00:24:09.440 --> 00:24:13.730
great I really
think it will change

00:24:13.730 --> 00:24:15.350
the experience for users.

00:24:15.350 --> 00:24:17.240
And you get much
higher conversions.

00:24:17.240 --> 00:24:18.580
And everyone will be happy.

00:24:18.580 --> 00:24:20.281
And we like happy people.

00:24:23.227 --> 00:24:26.010
Code wise, this is
what it looks like.

00:24:26.010 --> 00:24:29.390
So you will create a new
PaymentRequest object.

00:24:29.390 --> 00:24:31.130
And then the first
parameter you see

00:24:31.130 --> 00:24:34.070
here is just passing in
the different credit cards,

00:24:34.070 --> 00:24:37.430
in this case, that you support.

00:24:37.430 --> 00:24:42.590
And then the browser can use
the different available methods

00:24:42.590 --> 00:24:45.050
and then go through
all the other parts.

00:24:45.050 --> 00:24:47.630
These are all the line items
for what you're buying.

00:24:47.630 --> 00:24:49.970
And then finally
here at the bottom,

00:24:49.970 --> 00:24:52.580
you can set a Boolean whether
you want to request a shipping

00:24:52.580 --> 00:24:54.440
cost or not.

00:24:54.440 --> 00:24:57.770
And I do want to point out that
our implementation and also

00:24:57.770 --> 00:25:01.130
the code that you're seeing here
is based on the first Public

00:25:01.130 --> 00:25:02.910
Working draft by W3C.

00:25:02.910 --> 00:25:04.670
So it might change.

00:25:04.670 --> 00:25:06.440
Most likely it will
look just like this.

00:25:06.440 --> 00:25:10.340
But just a heads up that
it might actually change.

00:25:10.340 --> 00:25:13.070
So the user experience for
someone going in and buying

00:25:13.070 --> 00:25:17.550
something is that when you
choose to pay for something,

00:25:17.550 --> 00:25:19.850
this pops up.

00:25:19.850 --> 00:25:20.900
You choose pay.

00:25:20.900 --> 00:25:22.890
And then with the
shipping, for instance,

00:25:22.890 --> 00:25:25.510
if they requested
a shipping cost,

00:25:25.510 --> 00:25:27.710
you choose what kind
of shipping you want.

00:25:27.710 --> 00:25:29.190
And then you process request.

00:25:29.190 --> 00:25:31.700
And you bought something.

00:25:31.700 --> 00:25:33.410
Which I think this is amazing.

00:25:33.410 --> 00:25:36.640
I think this will
change things a lot.

00:25:36.640 --> 00:25:41.420
But of course, credit
cards isn't the only thing.

00:25:41.420 --> 00:25:44.530
We're also looking into other
different payment options.

00:25:44.530 --> 00:25:46.970
And we launched
Android Pay last year.

00:25:46.970 --> 00:25:50.270
And we've seen a really big
growth around Android Pay.

00:25:50.270 --> 00:25:52.760
We believe that it
needs to be on the web.

00:25:52.760 --> 00:25:56.840
And we see it as even more
secure tokenized version

00:25:56.840 --> 00:25:59.230
of your card.

00:25:59.230 --> 00:26:01.570
So as we saw before with
different payment methods,

00:26:01.570 --> 00:26:03.910
if you want to use something
else from credit cards,

00:26:03.910 --> 00:26:06.230
you can just add that
in the first parameter.

00:26:06.230 --> 00:26:08.720
So you would have Visa,
MasterCard, et cetera.

00:26:08.720 --> 00:26:12.040
And then you have a
URL to Android Pay.

00:26:12.040 --> 00:26:14.710
And down here, you can see
all the different parameters

00:26:14.710 --> 00:26:18.340
that you might need to
send in to Android Pay.

00:26:18.340 --> 00:26:20.890
And the idea with
this, right now we only

00:26:20.890 --> 00:26:21.760
support Android Pay.

00:26:21.760 --> 00:26:23.440
But the idea over
time, of course,

00:26:23.440 --> 00:26:26.770
is to support a number of other
different payment providers

00:26:26.770 --> 00:26:29.660
as well, which is vital
to make this work.

00:26:29.660 --> 00:26:33.130
So this API should look the
same over time no matter

00:26:33.130 --> 00:26:34.750
which payment provider you use.

00:26:34.750 --> 00:26:37.750
The only difference will
be maybe different values

00:26:37.750 --> 00:26:41.320
you will send in to actually
make the actual payment.

00:26:41.320 --> 00:26:45.460
And we started back
in May trying this out

00:26:45.460 --> 00:26:48.750
in Chrome Dev on Android.

00:26:48.750 --> 00:26:53.050
And then back in August,
we went into beta.

00:26:53.050 --> 00:26:56.830
And then we shipped it
in Chrome 53 for Android.

00:26:56.830 --> 00:26:58.780
And then next
year, we're looking

00:26:58.780 --> 00:27:03.010
to support more platforms and
also support more third party

00:27:03.010 --> 00:27:05.350
payment providers as well.

00:27:05.350 --> 00:27:09.340
And again, a few companies
have started working with this.

00:27:09.340 --> 00:27:14.380
So if you buy something
from these companies online

00:27:14.380 --> 00:27:18.400
or through mobile
websites, please let them

00:27:18.400 --> 00:27:19.870
know how it actually works.

00:27:19.870 --> 00:27:22.150
Let us know how it works.

00:27:22.150 --> 00:27:26.230
And let W3C know how it works,
because it's really, really

00:27:26.230 --> 00:27:27.610
important that we
get this right.

00:27:27.610 --> 00:27:30.910
And we can offer good payment
options for you on the web.

00:27:33.730 --> 00:27:36.250
So far we've talked about
making it way easier for users

00:27:36.250 --> 00:27:37.060
to log in.

00:27:37.060 --> 00:27:41.140
Everything's automatic,
automatic sign-ins, one tap

00:27:41.140 --> 00:27:43.030
payment and all of that.

00:27:43.030 --> 00:27:44.680
So what about
connecting the hardware?

00:27:49.800 --> 00:27:53.310
And the web has had access
to hardware for some time

00:27:53.310 --> 00:27:57.510
actually with accelerometers,
game controllers, camera,

00:27:57.510 --> 00:27:59.920
audio input and
output, and such.

00:27:59.920 --> 00:28:02.100
So when I talk about
hardware, I talk

00:28:02.100 --> 00:28:07.080
more about Bluetooth and
devices like heart rate sensors

00:28:07.080 --> 00:28:08.790
and similar.

00:28:08.790 --> 00:28:10.980
And usually when we
talk about Bluetooth,

00:28:10.980 --> 00:28:13.890
you talk about something
called BLE which

00:28:13.890 --> 00:28:15.570
is version four Bluetooth.

00:28:15.570 --> 00:28:19.610
And BLE stands for
Bluetooth Low Energy.

00:28:19.610 --> 00:28:23.630
And looking at the
evolution of transfer rates,

00:28:23.630 --> 00:28:27.630
we see in Wi-Fi and Ethernet,
it just gets faster and faster

00:28:27.630 --> 00:28:29.270
to transfer things.

00:28:29.270 --> 00:28:33.740
And with Bluetooth, it went
from one megabits per second,

00:28:33.740 --> 00:28:35.540
to three, to 54.

00:28:35.540 --> 00:28:39.720
So you would expect that
version four is amazing.

00:28:39.720 --> 00:28:43.620
Well, not really
what you expected.

00:28:43.620 --> 00:28:47.640
And the reason for this,
why transfer speed was

00:28:47.640 --> 00:28:53.400
cut down dramatically
and almost nonexistent,

00:28:53.400 --> 00:28:56.430
is because two main factors--

00:28:56.430 --> 00:28:57.690
power and cost.

00:28:57.690 --> 00:28:59.850
And with all of these
low energy devices,

00:28:59.850 --> 00:29:03.240
you want to make sure that
they use as less battery as

00:29:03.240 --> 00:29:06.660
possible, so it can last without
being charged or connected

00:29:06.660 --> 00:29:07.740
all the time.

00:29:07.740 --> 00:29:10.950
And the other part is the
cost of producing these.

00:29:10.950 --> 00:29:14.070
Producing something with a
lower transfer rate is cheaper.

00:29:14.070 --> 00:29:18.390
So we can produce more
different devices and faster.

00:29:18.390 --> 00:29:21.130
And through the
web, we've connected

00:29:21.130 --> 00:29:25.120
through remote controlled
racecars, Bluetooth Low Energy

00:29:25.120 --> 00:29:26.890
printers.

00:29:26.890 --> 00:29:32.310
You might recognize this guy,
the BB8 remote control robot.

00:29:32.310 --> 00:29:35.030
But it also connected
things like Dotty,

00:29:35.030 --> 00:29:37.750
which is a Bluetooth LED
notification display, so

00:29:37.750 --> 00:29:39.490
many different things.

00:29:39.490 --> 00:29:44.520
So I wonder, should I be
brave enough and try a demo?

00:29:44.520 --> 00:29:47.270
Yeah, thank you.

00:29:47.270 --> 00:29:48.230
We'll see.

00:29:48.230 --> 00:29:50.570
Well don't clap yet.

00:29:50.570 --> 00:29:53.900
We'll see how it goes.

00:29:53.900 --> 00:29:58.010
So this is a Bluetooth
Low Energy device

00:29:58.010 --> 00:29:59.690
called a Play Bulb Candle.

00:29:59.690 --> 00:30:01.590
It's basically just
setting the mood.

00:30:01.590 --> 00:30:03.631
And you're going to have
different colors and all

00:30:03.631 --> 00:30:04.360
of that.

00:30:04.360 --> 00:30:09.970
But what I can do is that
I can get my mobile phone.

00:30:14.890 --> 00:30:21.220
What I will be doing on my
phone is that I go into Chrome.

00:30:21.220 --> 00:30:24.080
And I load a website.

00:30:24.080 --> 00:30:25.670
And then I tap Connect.

00:30:25.670 --> 00:30:28.820
And I get a list of available
Bluetooth devices nearby.

00:30:28.820 --> 00:30:33.210
And I can see the
