00:31:34.860 --> 00:31:36.890
And when you work with
Bluetooth Low Energy,

00:31:36.890 --> 00:31:40.430
there are a few terms to
know, three different things.

00:31:40.430 --> 00:31:44.180
You have the central device,
which is the phone in this case

00:31:44.180 --> 00:31:44.930
.

00:31:44.930 --> 00:31:46.640
You have the peripheral
device, which

00:31:46.640 --> 00:31:49.100
is the candle or any kind of
Bluetooth Low Energy thing

00:31:49.100 --> 00:31:50.460
that you connect to.

00:31:50.460 --> 00:31:53.780
But you also have the GATT,
which is the generic ATTribute

00:31:53.780 --> 00:31:54.590
profile.

00:31:54.590 --> 00:31:57.500
So basically the Bluetooth
Low Energy device

00:31:57.500 --> 00:31:59.040
has a GATT server.

00:31:59.040 --> 00:32:01.280
And then you can
ask the GATT server

00:32:01.280 --> 00:32:04.010
of this candle what
kind of services

00:32:04.010 --> 00:32:07.640
and the characteristics
it supports.

00:32:07.640 --> 00:32:13.190
So with the coder, you can
call navigator.Bluetooth.

00:32:13.190 --> 00:32:16.280
And as you see, the first
parameter here is mandatory.

00:32:16.280 --> 00:32:19.220
And it is what kind of
service you want to ask for.

00:32:19.220 --> 00:32:23.570
And the reason for that is if
you asked for Bluetooth devices

00:32:23.570 --> 00:32:26.120
close to you, you will
get a very long list.

00:32:26.120 --> 00:32:28.130
So you only want to
ask for a device that

00:32:28.130 --> 00:32:32.850
actually supports the thing
that you want to do right now.

00:32:32.850 --> 00:32:36.120
Also the request
device method needs

00:32:36.120 --> 00:32:38.710
to be called with a user action.

00:32:38.710 --> 00:32:40.620
So basically you can't
just automatically do

00:32:40.620 --> 00:32:41.640
this for a user.

00:32:41.640 --> 00:32:44.910
They need to tap a button
or something like that.

00:32:44.910 --> 00:32:46.920
This, again, like
the other ones,

00:32:46.920 --> 00:32:49.434
it's only supported over HTTPS.

00:32:49.434 --> 00:32:50.850
But if you want
to try it out, you

00:32:50.850 --> 00:32:53.940
can also try it on local
host on your machines.

00:32:53.940 --> 00:32:57.290
And it will work as well.

00:32:57.290 --> 00:33:01.260
And once you actually manage
to pair with the device,

00:33:01.260 --> 00:33:05.880
you connect to the GATT
server of that device.

00:33:05.880 --> 00:33:09.160
And basically you get
back that connection.

00:33:09.160 --> 00:33:13.740
And once you've gotten that,
you can get the primary service,

00:33:13.740 --> 00:33:15.610
battery service in this case.

00:33:15.610 --> 00:33:18.840
And once you have that, you
can check the characteristic,

00:33:18.840 --> 00:33:20.680
which is the battery level.

00:33:20.680 --> 00:33:23.550
Once you have that, you
can read out the value

00:33:23.550 --> 00:33:29.600
and see, for instance, just the
actual battery of that device.

00:33:29.600 --> 00:33:32.652
Same thing with the
candle and changing it,

00:33:32.652 --> 00:33:34.110
the way we do it
with the candle is

00:33:34.110 --> 00:33:36.690
that you have the primary
service, which is the candle

00:33:36.690 --> 00:33:40.040
service UUID, and then
the characteristic, which

00:33:40.040 --> 00:33:42.320
is candle caller UUID.

00:33:42.320 --> 00:33:44.910
And then instead you call
the right value method.

00:33:44.910 --> 00:33:46.490
So basically you
pass in the caller,

00:33:46.490 --> 00:33:50.120
for instance, that you
want the candle to have.

00:33:50.120 --> 00:33:53.730
And if you look at these values
like candle service UUID,

00:33:53.730 --> 00:33:55.720
they seem magical.

00:33:55.720 --> 00:33:59.020
How do you know what
it's actually named?

00:33:59.020 --> 00:34:01.930
If you're lucky, when you get
a Bluetooth Low Energy device,

00:34:01.930 --> 00:34:04.840
it will have a programming
guide with all these things

00:34:04.840 --> 00:34:05.620
specified.

00:34:05.620 --> 00:34:10.179
But if not, you can install
control software on Android

00:34:10.179 --> 00:34:13.350
and also turn on the
developer options in Settings.

00:34:13.350 --> 00:34:15.940
And then you can capture
all the Bluetooth packets.

00:34:15.940 --> 00:34:17.098
And then you get the log.

00:34:17.098 --> 00:34:18.639
And within that log,
you can actually

00:34:18.639 --> 00:34:23.070
see the different values
and names of all of these.

00:34:23.070 --> 00:34:24.850
You can also have
event listeners.

00:34:24.850 --> 00:34:28.130
Like with this candle, I'm
glad it actually worked.

00:34:28.130 --> 00:34:29.830
But when you blow
it out, you can

00:34:29.830 --> 00:34:35.110
have an event listener to see if
the value of any characteristic

00:34:35.110 --> 00:34:35.920
is changing.

00:34:35.920 --> 00:34:38.940
So you can see, for instance,
oh, it was actually blown out.

00:34:38.940 --> 00:34:43.280
Now I'm going to do
something else with it.

00:34:43.280 --> 00:34:45.219
Then we have WebNFC coming.

00:34:54.870 --> 00:34:59.190
And it's basically what
it says, that on the web,

00:34:59.190 --> 00:35:02.070
you can connect
through NFC to devices

00:35:02.070 --> 00:35:07.980
nearby and get JSON back
and then parse that format.

00:35:07.980 --> 00:35:12.030
And I do recommend following
the work by a Danish friend

00:35:12.030 --> 00:35:14.040
of mine, Kenneth Christiansen.

00:35:14.040 --> 00:35:16.060
This is actually the best
picture I have of him.

00:35:16.060 --> 00:35:18.690
So I worked a long time
to get a better one.

00:35:18.690 --> 00:35:20.480
But I couldn't.

00:35:20.480 --> 00:35:22.730
And you should follow
his work, because he's

00:35:22.730 --> 00:35:25.940
working both with
the WebNFC stuff

00:35:25.940 --> 00:35:29.180
but also something
called Generic Sensors.

00:35:29.180 --> 00:35:31.030
And basically the idea
with Generic Sensors

00:35:31.030 --> 00:35:34.640
is that you would have a
generally specified API

00:35:34.640 --> 00:35:36.580
for different kinds of sensors.

00:35:36.580 --> 00:35:40.670
So you could have direct tire
pressure sensor for your car.

00:35:40.670 --> 00:35:42.420
So if you wanted,
through JavaScript,

00:35:42.420 --> 00:35:46.010
to check the value of
your left front tire

00:35:46.010 --> 00:35:50.332
or something like that,
you can get that back.

00:35:50.332 --> 00:35:52.040
And also you could
work with other things

00:35:52.040 --> 00:35:55.640
like geo location
sensors and other values

00:35:55.640 --> 00:35:59.000
and get on error an on
change event handlers.

00:35:59.000 --> 00:36:01.820
And the idea with this
and the previous example,

00:36:01.820 --> 00:36:03.784
it could basically
be any sensor.

00:36:03.784 --> 00:36:06.200
And it should be implemented
and accessed in the same way.

00:36:06.200 --> 00:36:07.820
You just have the
name of the sensor

00:36:07.820 --> 00:36:12.190
and then the same calls,
the same methods, et cetera.

00:36:12.190 --> 00:36:14.460
And talking about
physical devices

00:36:14.460 --> 00:36:17.280
and talking about
web Bluetooth, I

00:36:17.280 --> 00:36:19.890
want to talk briefly about
another project called

00:36:19.890 --> 00:36:21.190
Physical Web.

00:36:21.190 --> 00:36:24.000
And Physical Web is
basically about beacons.

00:36:24.000 --> 00:36:27.140
You would have really,
really small things

00:36:27.140 --> 00:36:28.140
that they put out there.

00:36:28.140 --> 00:36:32.880
And the only thing that they
do is that a broadcast a URL.

00:36:32.880 --> 00:36:36.210
So if you're close to one
of these with your device,

00:36:36.210 --> 00:36:39.750
you will get a notification
on your phone with the URL.

00:36:39.750 --> 00:36:41.340
And then you tap
that notification.

00:36:41.340 --> 00:36:43.120
And it will take
you to that URL.

00:36:43.120 --> 00:36:47.230
And it could be any kind of
information in that page.

00:36:47.230 --> 00:36:49.260
But the interesting
part is about,

00:36:49.260 --> 00:36:51.900
with the physical
beacons, it's only things

00:36:51.900 --> 00:36:54.540
that you are actually close to.

00:36:54.540 --> 00:36:56.400
So if you would walk
around in a mall,

00:36:56.400 --> 00:36:59.190
you can walk by a
store with shoes.

00:36:59.190 --> 00:37:00.422
And it could send out a URL.

00:37:00.422 --> 00:37:01.380
And you would tap that.

00:37:01.380 --> 00:37:03.600
And it will tell you that
they have a sale today,

00:37:03.600 --> 00:37:05.770
for instance.

00:37:05.770 --> 00:37:07.710
Or if you're on
the train station,

00:37:07.710 --> 00:37:09.550
you can get a notification.

00:37:09.550 --> 00:37:13.290
And then you can follow the
URL and see the timetable.

00:37:13.290 --> 00:37:15.630
Or parking your car,
you can actually

00:37:15.630 --> 00:37:17.634
access the parking meter
from within the car

00:37:17.634 --> 00:37:19.050
so you don't even
have to get out.

00:37:19.050 --> 00:37:22.470
And you can pay for
parking, et cetera.

00:37:22.470 --> 00:37:25.670
So it's an easy way of
just giving information

00:37:25.670 --> 00:37:29.580
to people close to where
they are right now.

00:37:29.580 --> 00:37:32.820
But it also in the future,
looking into interacting more

00:37:32.820 --> 00:37:34.710
with these beacons
through something

00:37:34.710 --> 00:37:37.320
called referring device.

00:37:37.320 --> 00:37:41.180
And the idea with this is
that with the physical beacons

00:37:41.180 --> 00:37:44.390
that you could connect to them
through their GATT server.

00:37:44.390 --> 00:37:47.830
And then you can also start
to control things on them

00:37:47.830 --> 00:37:51.380
or directly interface
with them through the web.

00:37:51.380 --> 00:37:55.400
And we've seen a bunch of
experimental implementations

00:37:55.400 --> 00:37:58.430
so far with web Bluetooth.

00:37:58.430 --> 00:38:01.010
Chrome and Opera has had
the first implementations.

00:38:01.010 --> 00:38:03.710
And we work on making
them more and more stable.

00:38:03.710 --> 00:38:05.970
And we've seen a
really huge developer

00:38:05.970 --> 00:38:09.140
interest with web Bluetooth and
the things that we can create.

00:38:09.140 --> 00:38:11.630
We're hoping to see more
browsers start implementing it

00:38:11.630 --> 00:38:14.825
soon as well.

00:38:14.825 --> 00:38:19.200
I also want to talk about
virtual reality briefly.

00:38:19.200 --> 00:38:25.500
And we've seen good
progress on 1.0 of the API.

00:38:25.500 --> 00:38:27.330
So about two months
ago, the first version

00:38:27.330 --> 00:38:28.740
landed in Firefox.

00:38:28.740 --> 00:38:31.320
And they've been doing
really great work on v.r.

00:38:31.320 --> 00:38:32.760
VR.

00:38:32.760 --> 00:38:36.900
We're getting closer to that
as well with Chrome this year.

00:38:36.900 --> 00:38:41.940
And Microsoft Edge has also
begun development on VR

00:38:41.940 --> 00:38:43.740
in the browser.

00:38:43.740 --> 00:38:48.430
And about six months ago,
we have a one time per year

00:38:48.430 --> 00:38:52.440
our a big developer
conference called Google I/O.

00:38:52.440 --> 00:38:56.250
And at Google I/O, we,
six months ago in May, we

00:38:56.250 --> 00:38:59.010
announced something
called Daydream.

00:38:59.010 --> 00:39:01.080
And basically what
Daydream is, it's

00:39:01.080 --> 00:39:04.470
a specification
for VR experiences.

00:39:04.470 --> 00:39:09.270
So it's more of having a
reference design for a headset

00:39:09.270 --> 00:39:11.820
that should have a headband.

00:39:11.820 --> 00:39:14.840
It should have a remote
control similar to this one.

00:39:14.840 --> 00:39:17.247
And at the top of the remote
control, it's a clicker.

00:39:17.247 --> 00:39:18.330
But it's also a touch pad.

00:39:18.330 --> 00:39:20.600
So you can move your
thumb around and control

00:39:20.600 --> 00:39:21.700
things and all of that.

00:39:21.700 --> 00:39:24.240
And then you have below
that one the action button,

00:39:24.240 --> 00:39:26.650
and then one home button.

00:39:26.650 --> 00:39:31.410
And the first ones we shipped
was with one headset made out

00:39:31.410 --> 00:39:34.399
of cloth, which is
soft and nice to wear,

00:39:34.399 --> 00:39:36.690
because especially if you're
going to wear it over time

00:39:36.690 --> 00:39:38.520
and watching videos or
something like that,

00:39:38.520 --> 00:39:41.700
it should be comfortable and
not like a big piece of plastic

00:39:41.700 --> 00:39:43.140
in your face.

00:39:43.140 --> 00:39:46.150
People don't seem to like that.

00:39:46.150 --> 00:39:48.519
But that's only
one of the options.

00:39:48.519 --> 00:39:50.560
But we're seeing a number
of different providers,

00:39:50.560 --> 00:39:54.020
from Samsung and LG and
more also building devices.

00:39:54.020 --> 00:39:56.480
So it's not a Google-only thing.

00:39:56.480 --> 00:39:58.450
But it's more of
something that will work

00:39:58.450 --> 00:39:59.900
across the board on Android.

00:39:59.900 --> 00:40:03.010
And you're going to see more
headsets, more remote controls,

00:40:03.010 --> 00:40:04.750
and more experiences.

00:40:04.750 --> 00:40:06.640
And if you're
interested in VR, I

00:40:06.640 --> 00:40:12.270
do recommend a project by
Mozilla called A-Frame.

00:40:12.270 --> 00:40:15.700
And it's designed by
the Mozilla VR team.

00:40:15.700 --> 00:40:17.320
And basically what
it does is that it

00:40:17.320 --> 00:40:23.710
wraps a library called 3.js
and WebGL in custom elements

00:40:23.710 --> 00:40:24.640
in HTML.

00:40:24.640 --> 00:40:26.740
So it's a really nice
way of getting started,

00:40:26.740 --> 00:40:31.090
playing with it, see
if you like it or not.

00:40:31.090 --> 00:40:32.710
A few months ago
as well, we also

00:40:32.710 --> 00:40:35.750
shipped something called
VR View for the web.

00:40:35.750 --> 00:40:39.790
So if you have a content
like 360 images or 360 videos

00:40:39.790 --> 00:40:42.580
or something like that,
basically what you do

00:40:42.580 --> 00:40:45.375
is that you embed it in your
web page with an I-frame.

00:40:45.375 --> 00:40:46.210
You point to a URL.

00:40:46.210 --> 00:40:49.840
And you have a small JavaScript
library to handle it.

00:40:49.840 --> 00:40:52.660
And if you're on a desktop
computer, and if you click,

00:40:52.660 --> 00:40:54.940
you can click and drag
and look around and then

00:40:54.940 --> 00:40:56.140
see what it's like.

00:40:56.140 --> 00:41:01.150
But also if you have a VR
viewer, Cardboard or similar,

00:41:01.150 --> 00:41:02.725
you can just put your phone in.

00:41:02.725 --> 00:41:06.750
